Use `cc.director.runScene` to replace the current scene:

```typescript
// Create and run a new scene
const gameScene = new GameScene();
cc.director.runScene(gameScene);

// With a fade transition (0.5 seconds)
const transition = new cc.TransitionFade(0.5, gameScene);
cc.director.runScene(transition);
```

`runScene` replaces the current scene entirely. The old scene is destroyed. For modal/overlay patterns where you want to return to the previous scene, use `pushScene`/`popScene` instead.

Use `pushScene` to overlay a new scene and `popScene` to return:

```typescript
// Push the pause menu on top of the game
const pauseMenu = new PauseMenuScene();
cc.director.pushScene(pauseMenu);

// In the pause menu, return to the game:
cc.director.popScene();

// Pop all scenes back to the root
cc.director.popToRootScene();

// Pop to a specific stack level
cc.director.popToSceneStackLevel(1);
```

The push/pop pattern maintains a scene stack. The underlying game scene stays in memory and resumes when you pop back to it. This is ideal for pause menus, settings screens, and inventory overlays.

```typescript
class PauseMenuScene extends cc.Scene {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        const resumeBtn = new cc.MenuItemFont('Resume', () => {
            cc.director.popScene(); // return to game
        });
        const menu = new cc.Menu(resumeBtn);
        this.addChild(menu);
    }
}
```

Use `cc.director.getWinSize()` for the design resolution:

```typescript
const winSize: cc.Size = cc.director.getWinSize();
const centerX = winSize.width / 2;
const centerY = winSize.height / 2;

// Position a sprite at center
sprite.setPosition(centerX, centerY);

// Other size methods:
const pixelSize = cc.director.getWinSizeInPixels();  // actual pixels
const visibleSize = cc.director.getVisibleSize();     // visible area
const origin = cc.director.getVisibleOrigin();        // visible area origin

// Safe area for notched devices
const safeRect = cc.director.getSafeAreaRect();
```

`getWinSize()` returns the design resolution in points. `getWinSizeInPixels()` returns the actual pixel resolution. `getVisibleSize()` and `getVisibleOrigin()` account for letterboxing when the aspect ratio doesn't match.

Use `cc.director.pause()` and `cc.director.resume()`:

```typescript
// Pause the entire game (stops scheduler, actions, and rendering updates)
cc.director.pause();

// Check if paused
if (cc.director.isPaused()) {
    cc.log('Game is paused');
}

// Resume
cc.director.resume();
```

Complete pause system:
```typescript
class PauseManager {
    private static _isPaused: boolean = false;

    static toggle(): void {
        if (PauseManager._isPaused) {
            cc.director.resume();
        } else {
            cc.director.pause();
        }
        PauseManager._isPaused = !PauseManager._isPaused;
    }

    static get isPaused(): boolean {
        return cc.director.isPaused();
    }
}
```

Note: `cc.director.pause()` stops ALL scheduled updates and actions globally. For selective pausing (e.g., pause gameplay but keep UI animating), use `cc.director.getScheduler().pauseTarget()` or `cc.director.getActionManager().pauseTarget()` on specific nodes.

Use `cc.director.setAnimationInterval` with the interval in seconds:

```typescript
// Set to 60 FPS (default)
cc.director.setAnimationInterval(1 / 60);

// Set to 30 FPS (for battery saving)
cc.director.setAnimationInterval(1 / 30);

// Get current interval
const interval = cc.director.getAnimationInterval(); // e.g., 0.01667 for 60fps
const targetFPS = Math.round(1 / interval);
cc.log('Target FPS:', targetFPS);

// Get actual frame time
const dt = cc.director.getDeltaTime();         // seconds since last frame
const spf = cc.director.getSecondsPerFrame(); // actual seconds per frame
const totalFrames = cc.director.getTotalFrames();
cc.log('Actual FPS:', Math.round(1 / spf));
```

The parameter is the **interval between frames in seconds**, not the FPS value. So 60 FPS = 1/60, 30 FPS = 1/30.

Extend `cc.Scene` and add layers in `onEnter`:

```typescript
class GameScene extends cc.Scene {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        const gameLayer = new GameLayer();
        this.addChild(gameLayer);
    }
}

class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        const sprite = new cc.Sprite('res/hero.png');
        sprite.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height / 2);
        this.addChild(sprite);
    }
}

// Run the scene
cc.director.runScene(new GameScene());
```

`cc.Scene` extends `cc.Node` and serves as the root container. Layers organize content within a scene (e.g., background layer, game layer, UI layer). Always call `super.onEnter()` before your initialization code.

Wrap the target scene in a `cc.TransitionFade` before passing to `runScene`:

```typescript
// Basic fade transition
const nextScene = new GameScene();
const transition = new cc.TransitionFade(0.5, nextScene);
cc.director.runScene(transition);
```

`cc.TransitionFade` extends `cc.TransitionScene` which extends `cc.Scene`:

```typescript
// Constructor signature
new cc.TransitionFade(duration: number, scene: cc.Scene)
```

Complete scene manager with transitions:
```typescript
class SceneManager {
    private static readonly TRANSITION_DURATION = 0.5;

    static goTo(scene: cc.Scene): void {
        const transition = new cc.TransitionFade(
            SceneManager.TRANSITION_DURATION,
            scene
        );
        cc.director.runScene(transition);
    }

    static goToGame(): void {
        SceneManager.goTo(new GameScene());
    }

    static goToMenu(): void {
        SceneManager.goTo(new MenuScene());
    }

    static goToGameOver(): void {
        SceneManager.goTo(new GameOverScene());
    }
}
```

`cc.TransitionScene` is the base class for all transitions. `cc.TransitionFade` fades to black and then fades in the new scene.

Access the scheduler singleton to set time scale for slow-motion or fast-forward effects:

```typescript
const scheduler = cc.director.getScheduler();

// Slow motion (half speed)
scheduler.setTimeScale(0.5);

// Normal speed
scheduler.setTimeScale(1.0);

// Fast forward (double speed)
