```

Common pattern for game pause:
```typescript
class GamePauseController {
    private _pausedTargets: cc.Node[] = [];

    pause(): void {
        this._pausedTargets = cc.director.getActionManager().pauseAllRunningActions();
        cc.log('Paused', this._pausedTargets.length, 'targets');
    }

    resume(): void {
        cc.director.getActionManager().resumeTargets(this._pausedTargets);
        this._pausedTargets = [];
    }
}
```

Use `getDeltaTime()` to get the time elapsed since the last frame:

```typescript
cc.director.getDeltaTime(): number  // seconds since last frame
```

Multiply velocities by delta time for consistent movement regardless of frame rate:

```typescript
class Player extends cc.Sprite {
    private static readonly SPEED = 200; // pixels per second

    update(dt: number): void {
        // dt is already provided by the scheduler,
        // but you can also get it from director:
        // const dt = cc.director.getDeltaTime();

        if (this._movingRight) {
            this.x += Player.SPEED * dt;
        }
    }
}

// Related timing methods:
cc.director.getSecondsPerFrame()   // actual time per frame
cc.director.getTotalFrames()       // total frames rendered
cc.director.getAnimationInterval() // target frame interval (e.g., 1/60)
```

At 60 FPS, `dt` is approximately 0.0167 seconds. At 30 FPS, it's approximately 0.033 seconds. Using `dt` ensures movement speed is consistent regardless of frame rate fluctuations.

