cc.loader.releaseAll();
```

`cc.director.purgeCachedData()` clears all cached textures, sprite frames, and animations:

```typescript
cc.director.purgeCachedData(): void
```

Use it during scene transitions to free memory:

```typescript
class SceneTransition {
    static switchTo(newScene: cc.Scene, purge: boolean = true): void {
        if (purge) {
            // Release all cached resources
            cc.director.purgeCachedData();
            cc.log('Cached data purged');
        }
        cc.director.runScene(new cc.TransitionFade(0.5, newScene));
    }
}

// Purge during heavy scene transitions
SceneTransition.switchTo(new GameScene(), true);

// Don't purge for lightweight overlays
SceneTransition.switchTo(new SettingsScene(), false);
```

This clears:
- `cc.textureCache` — all loaded textures
- `cc.spriteFrameCache` — all sprite frame definitions
- `cc.animationCache` — all animation data

After purging, any resources needed by the new scene must be reloaded. Use selectively — purging everything before a scene that shares assets with the current scene will cause unnecessary reloading.

The director fires events at specific points in the frame loop:

```typescript
cc.Director.EVENT_AFTER_DRAW: string    // after rendering each frame
cc.Director.EVENT_AFTER_UPDATE: string  // after all scheduled updates
cc.Director.EVENT_AFTER_VISIT: string   // after visiting scene graph
cc.Director.EVENT_PROJECTION_CHANGED: string // when projection changes
```

Listen for these events using `cc.eventManager.addCustomListener`:

```typescript
// Execute code after all updates complete each frame
const listener = cc.eventManager.addCustomListener(
    cc.Director.EVENT_AFTER_UPDATE,
    (event: cc.Event) => {
        // Physics resolution, collision checking, etc.
        resolveCollisions();
    }
);

// Execute code after rendering
cc.eventManager.addCustomListener(
    cc.Director.EVENT_AFTER_DRAW,
    (event: cc.Event) => {
        // Post-processing, screenshot capture, etc.
    }
);
```

Projection constants:
```typescript
cc.Director.PROJECTION_2D: number  // orthographic projection
cc.Director.PROJECTION_3D: number  // perspective projection (default)
```

These events are useful for systems that need to run at specific points in the frame lifecycle, like physics or post-processing.

Use `convertToGL` and `convertToUI` for coordinate system conversion:

```typescript
// UI coordinates (origin top-left, Y down) → GL coordinates (origin bottom-left, Y up)
const glPoint = cc.director.convertToGL(uiPoint: cc.Point): cc.Point

// GL coordinates → UI coordinates
const uiPoint = cc.director.convertToUI(glPoint: cc.Point): cc.Point
```

Examples:
```typescript
// Convert a screen tap (UI space) to game world (GL space)
const screenTap = cc.p(100, 50);  // top-left origin
const worldPos = cc.director.convertToGL(screenTap);
cc.log('World position:', worldPos.x, worldPos.y);

// Convert a game object position to screen coordinates
const spritePos = sprite.getPosition();
const screenPos = cc.director.convertToUI(spritePos);
cc.log('Screen position:', screenPos.x, screenPos.y);

// Useful for interfacing with HTML DOM elements in H5
