Complete the code for a scene that automatically transitions to the next scene after a countdown:

```typescript
class CountdownScene extends cc.Scene {
    private _seconds: number;
    private _nextScene: cc.Scene;
    // TODO: show countdown, transition when done
}
```

output:
```typescript
class CountdownScene extends cc.Scene {
    private _seconds: number;
    private _nextSceneFactory: () => cc.Scene;
    private _label: cc.LabelTTF;
    private _remaining: number;

    constructor(seconds: number, nextSceneFactory: () => cc.Scene) {
        super();
        this._seconds = seconds;
        this._nextSceneFactory = nextSceneFactory;
    }

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._remaining = this._seconds;

        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        this._label = new cc.LabelTTF(
            this._remaining.toString(),
            'Arial',
            72
        );
        this._label.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height / 2);
        this.addChild(this._label);

        this.schedule(this.tick, 1.0, this._seconds - 1, 0);
    }

    private tick(): void {
        this._remaining--;
        if (this._remaining <= 0) {
            this._label.setString('GO!');
            this.unschedule(this.tick);
            this.scheduleOnce(() => {
                const next = this._nextSceneFactory();
                cc.director.runScene(new cc.TransitionFade(0.3, next));
            }, 0.5);
        } else {
            this._label.setString(this._remaining.toString());
            // Scale animation
            this._label.setScale(1.5);
            this._label.runAction(cc.scaleTo(0.3, 1.0));
        }
    }
}

// Usage:
cc.director.runScene(new CountdownScene(3, () => new GameScene()));
```

The countdown ticks every second, shows an animated number, displays "GO!" at zero, then transitions to the target scene.

Use `scheduleUpdateForTarget` to control the order in which nodes receive `update` calls:

```typescript
const scheduler = cc.director.getScheduler();

// Lower priority number = called first
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(
    physicsManager,  // target (must implement update(dt))
    -10,             // priority: runs before default (0)
    false            // not paused
);

scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(
    gameLogic,
    0,               // default priority
    false
);

scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(
    renderManager,
    10,              // runs after default
    false
);
```

This ensures a deterministic update order:
1. Physics (priority -10) — updates positions
2. Game logic (priority 0) — checks collisions, applies rules
3. Render (priority 10) — updates visual state

Unschedule:
```typescript
scheduler.unscheduleUpdateForTarget(physicsManager);
```

The targets must implement an `update(dt: number)` method:
```typescript
class PhysicsManager extends cc.Class {
    update(dt: number): void {
        // Physics step
    }
}
```

Note: `node.scheduleUpdate()` uses priority 0 by default. Use the scheduler directly when you need explicit ordering.

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this code that tries to resume a game after showing a popup:

```typescript
class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    showPopup(): void {
        cc.director.pause();
        const popup = new PopupLayer(() => {
            cc.director.resume();
            cc.director.popScene();
        });
        cc.director.pushScene(popup);
    }
}
```

output:
The bug is the order of operations. `cc.director.pause()` is called **before** `pushScene`. When paused, the director stops processing — meaning `pushScene` may not work correctly because the main loop is paused.

Also, `resume()` is called before `popScene()`. The resume happens in the popup's scene context, then pop switches back — the ordering can cause a flash or missed frame.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    showPopup(): void {
        // Push the popup first, THEN the popup can handle pausing
        const popup = new PopupScene(() => {
            cc.director.popScene();
            // Resume after popping back to game scene
        });
        cc.director.pushScene(popup);
    }
}

class PopupScene extends cc.Scene {
    private _onDismiss: () => void;

    constructor(onDismiss: () => void) {
        super();
        this._onDismiss = onDismiss;
    }

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        // The underlying game scene is already "paused" because
        // pushScene stops it from updating
        const closeBtn = new cc.MenuItemFont('Close', () => {
            this._onDismiss();
        });
        const menu = new cc.Menu(closeBtn);
        this.addChild(menu);
    }
}
```

`pushScene` already effectively pauses the background scene (it stops receiving updates). There's no need to call `cc.director.pause()` separately. Using `pause()`/`resume()` with push/pop leads to state management complexity.

`popToSceneStackLevel` pops the scene stack down to a specific depth:

```typescript
cc.director.popToSceneStackLevel(level: number): void
```

Stack levels are 0-based:
- Level 0: empty (results in `end()`)
- Level 1: root scene only
- Level N: keep N scenes on stack

```typescript
// Example navigation flow:
// Stack: [MenuScene]  (level 1)
cc.director.runScene(new MenuScene());

// Stack: [MenuScene, GameScene]  (level 2)
cc.director.pushScene(new GameScene());

// Stack: [MenuScene, GameScene, PauseScene]  (level 3)
cc.director.pushScene(new PauseScene());

// Stack: [MenuScene, GameScene, PauseScene, SettingsScene]  (level 4)
cc.director.pushScene(new SettingsScene());

// Pop back to GameScene (level 2)
cc.director.popToSceneStackLevel(2);
// Stack: [MenuScene, GameScene]

// Pop to root (level 1)
cc.director.popToRootScene(); // equivalent to popToSceneStackLevel(1)
// Stack: [MenuScene]
```

This is useful for "back to game" buttons in deeply nested menus:
```typescript
class DeepMenu {
    static backToGame(): void {
        cc.director.popToSceneStackLevel(2); // Menu + Game
    }

    static backToMainMenu(): void {
        cc.director.popToRootScene(); // Just Menu
    }
}
```

`pauseAllTargetsWithMinPriority` pauses only targets at or above a given priority:

```typescript
scheduler.pauseAllTargetsWithMinPriority(minPriority: number): void
```

This lets you pause gameplay while keeping critical systems running:

```typescript
const scheduler = cc.director.getScheduler();

// Priority scheme:
// -100: System (always runs)
// -50: UI (runs during pause)
// 0: Gameplay (paused during pause)
// 50: VFX (paused during pause)

// Register with explicit priorities
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(systemManager, -100, false);
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(uiManager, -50, false);
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(gameplayManager, 0, false);
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(vfxManager, 50, false);

// Pause only gameplay and VFX (priority >= 0)
scheduler.pauseAllTargetsWithMinPriority(0);
// systemManager and uiManager keep running

// Resume all
scheduler.resumeTargets([gameplayManager, vfxManager]);
```

This is more surgical than `cc.director.pause()` which stops everything. Use it when you need the UI to remain interactive during a game pause.

instruction:
Review this code for loading and releasing resources:

```typescript
class ResourceHandler {
    loadLevel(id: number): void {
        cc.loader.load(['res/level' + id + '.json'], () => {
            const data = cc.loader.getRes('res/level' + id);
            this.buildLevel(data);
        });
    }
}
```

output:
Issues found:

1. **Wrong key in `getRes`.** The loaded resource key is `'res/level' + id + '.json'` (with extension), but `getRes` is called with `'res/level' + id` (without `.json`). The key must match exactly.

2. **No error handling.** The callback doesn't check for errors.

3. **No null check on `data`.** If `getRes` returns null (due to the key mismatch), `buildLevel` will crash.

4. **Resource never released.** Loaded JSON stays in cache forever.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class ResourceHandler {
    private static readonly LEVEL_PATH_PREFIX = 'res/level';

    private getLevelPath(id: number): string {
        return ResourceHandler.LEVEL_PATH_PREFIX + id + '.json';
    }

    loadLevel(id: number): void {
        const path = this.getLevelPath(id);
        cc.loader.load([path], (err) => {
            if (err) {
                cc.error('Failed to load level', id, err);
                return;
            }
            const data = cc.loader.getRes(path); // FIX: use exact path
            if (!data) {
                cc.error('Level data is null for', path);
                return;
            }
            this.buildLevel(data);
        });
    }

    releaseLevel(id: number): void {
        cc.loader.release(this.getLevelPath(id));
    }
}
```

Key rule: the string passed to `getRes` must be **exactly** the same as the string passed to `load`.

Detect orientation and adjust layout using director methods:

```typescript
class AdaptiveScene extends cc.Scene {
    private _isLandscape: boolean;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this.detectOrientation();
        this.layoutForOrientation();
        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    private detectOrientation(): void {
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        this._isLandscape = winSize.width > winSize.height;
    }

    private layoutForOrientation(): void {
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        const cx = winSize.width / 2;
        const cy = winSize.height / 2;

        if (this._isLandscape) {
            this.layoutLandscape(winSize, cx, cy);
        } else {
            this.layoutPortrait(winSize, cx, cy);
        }
    }

    private layoutLandscape(size: cc.Size, cx: number, cy: number): void {
        // Side-by-side layout
        cc.log('Landscape:', size.width, 'x', size.height);
    }

    private layoutPortrait(size: cc.Size, cx: number, cy: number): void {
        // Stacked layout
        cc.log('Portrait:', size.width, 'x', size.height);
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        // Check for orientation change
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        const nowLandscape = winSize.width > winSize.height;
        if (nowLandscape !== this._isLandscape) {
            this._isLandscape = nowLandscape;
            this.layoutForOrientation();
        }
    }
}
```

Use `cc.director.getWinSize()` each frame to detect orientation changes, then re-layout the UI accordingly.

Use removeAllActionsFromTarget to stop and remove every action running on a node:

```typescript
const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(mySprite, true);
```

The second param (forceDelete) when true removes even locked actions. Common cleanup pattern:

```typescript
class Enemy extends cc.Sprite {
    destroy(): void {
        const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
        mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(this, true);
        this.removeFromParent();
    }
}

// Batch cleanup
function cleanupAll(nodes: cc.Node[]): void {
    const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
    for (const node of nodes) {
        mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(node, true);
        node.removeFromParent();
    }
}
```

This is the ActionManager equivalent of `node.stopAllActions()`. Use the manager directly when you need to clean up nodes you do not have direct references to.

